I think this is because #2277 added stringio to the Gemfile.lock, which passenger doesn't like.  https://github.com/pulibrary/princeton_ansible/pull/4498 would likely fix that issue.

I saw the following in the nginx logs from datadog:

```
Error: The application encountered the following error: You have already activated stringio 3.0.1, but your Gemfile requires stringio 3.1.0. Since stringio is a default gem, you can either remove your dependency on it or try updating to a newer version of bundler that supports stringio as a default gem. (Gem::LoadError)
```
Discussed on 12/19. Will check back in January to collaborate on the fix from ansible 4498.

orangelight.title: Update Paging and ReCAP Request Email Templates for End Users

comments.body:
Rebooted the Globus machine and everything is back to normal (at least for now). 

Re-ran the self diagnostic immediately after the reboot and the number of GridFTP processes is very low, as expected. We'll see how long before they creep up again.

```
== diagnostic: systemctl status globus-gridftp-server --no-pager --lines 10 ==
● globus-gridftp-server.service - Globus Connect GridFTP Service
     Loaded: loaded (/lib/systemd/system/globus-gridftp-server.service; enabled; vendor preset: enabled)
     Active: active (running) since Tue 2023-12-19 16:03:16 UTC; 3min 3s ago
    Process: 474 ExecStart=/usr/sbin/globus-gridftp-server -S -c /etc/gridftp.conf -C /etc/gridftp.d -pidfile /run/globus-gridftp-server.pid (code=exited, status=0/SUCCESS)
   Main PID: 546 (globus-gridftp-)
      Tasks: 1 (limit: 9384)
     Memory: 5.1M
     CGroup: /system.slice/globus-gridftp-server.service
             └─546 /usr/sbin/globus-gridftp-server -c /etc/gridftp.conf -C /etc/gridftp.d -pidfile /run/globus-gridftp-server.pid -no-detach -config-base-path /

Dec 19 16:03:16 pdc-globus-prod-postcuration systemd[1]: Starting Globus Connect GridFTP Service...
Dec 19 16:03:16 pdc-globus-prod-postcuration systemd[1]: Started Globus Connect GridFTP Service.
```

Full diagnostic: https://drive.google.com/file/d/1_-V5vCfrk8VipDzfMitnLTFxuBczYo2Y/view?usp=drive_link

Carolyn found that we have several instances of the error "RECV buffer size may not be properly set. Requested size = 65536, actualy size = 131072" in our logs (`/var/log/gridftp.log`). 

Added this information to the Globus ticket to see if it means something to them.

We tried downloading multiple files simultaneously from PDC Describe staging (https://pdc-describe-staging.princeton.edu/describe/works/498) and see if we can see Globus creating multiple process while the downloads happens. We never saw any extra processes running when issuing `globus-connect-server self-diagnostic` while the downloads were happening. 

In production we also downloaded a dataset (with multiple files) using the Globus Personal Connect client and we did not see no extra process being created either.

Globus responded with the following:

```
Usually a process in state 'S' is waiting on I/O. 
 
Do any of your storage gateways have mapping policy that maps Globus users to the 'gcsweb' local user?
```

And then: 

```
Are these processes still still up? If so, what does this show:
 

lsof -u gcsweb

 
Please send us that, but also take a look at the open files and see if you recognize anything that might 
be in a path on one of the collections your endpoint exposes and let us know if you see anything in 
that regard.
```

Regarding the buffer size error:
```
    “RECV buffer size may not be properly set.  Requested size = 65536, actualy size = 131072”

 This can be ignored and is expected. The buffer size is handled automatically now - and has been for some time. 
This is an old warning and our devs have intention to simply suppress it in a future release.
```

AWS reports a very high network traffic in our EC2 instance at the time of the outages

![network_packets_out](https://github.com/pulibrary/pdc_describe/assets/568286/701e9286-3821-4592-9971-4ebd180e7dc5)
@kayiwa has run this from the branch, merging so we don't run from main and undo this!
